GOplotclusterProfilerpaper

Requirement description

Display the enrichment analysis results of clusterProfiler using GOplot and draw the data in the paper Image

https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-017-01195-y

fromhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-017-01195-y

https://www.karger.com/Article/FullText/492519

fromhttps://www.karger.com/Article/FullText/492519

clusterProfilerGOplot

GOclusterProfilerGOplotGOplot

clusterProfilerGOKEGGDiseaesReactomeDAVIDMSigDBenrichplotgseaplot2GSEApathwayJavaGSEAhttps://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/AamfRz0BUENCi_1P0P-Ruw

Application scenarios

Suitable for: those who want to use clusterProfiler for enrichment analysis and GOplot to display results, but do not know how to connect the two.

Taking GO as an example, obtain the enrichment analysis results of clusterProfiler, generate the required format for GOplot, and use GOplot to draw Picture.

In addition to being proficient in GO enrichment analysis, clusterProfiler can also use annotation libraries such as KEGG, Disseales, Reactor, DAVID, MSigDB, etc. for enrichment analysis. In addition, enrichplots built-in gseaplot2 function can generate vector graphs of GSEA results and draw multiple pathways onto the same graph, perfectly replacing the Java version of GSEA. See this article:< https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/AamfRz0BUENCi_1P0P-Ruw>

IDENTREZ IDvery_easy_input_**.csv

gene symbolensembl ID

Obtain the correspondence between ENTREZ ID and gene name

If your gene ID is already ENTREZ ID and saved in the format of very easy input * *. csv, you can skip this step and directly enter enrichment analysis

Find the corresponding ensembl ID based on the gene symbol name. The conversion code for model organisms and non model organisms is slightly different. Depending on your species, choose to run one of the following two segments.

ENTREZ ID

18OrgDb = "org.Mm.eg.db"

Rhttp://bioconductor.org/packages/release/BiocViews.html#___OrgDb

ENTREZ ID

Obtaining ENTREZ IDs for humans and model organisms

Taking the mouse data in the example article as an example, the other 18 species only need to change the OrgDb= org. Mm. eg. db parameter

Please refer to this page for the R package names corresponding to specific species:< http://bioconductor.org/packages/release/BiocViews.html#___OrgDb >

If the species you are concerned about is not in this list, please skip this step and go directly to Obtaining ENTREZ ID for Non model Organisms

# CSV | Read gene symbols and expression data from CSV file
gsym.fc <- read.csv("easy_input_Mm.csv", as.is = T)
#  | Check the dimensions (rows and columns) of the data
dim(gsym.fc)
## [1] 201   2
# ID | View available ID types (commented out)
# keytypes(org.Mm.eg.db)

# ENTREZ ID | Convert gene symbols to ENTREZ IDs
gsym.id <- bitr(gsym.fc$SYMBOL,         #  | Gene symbol column
                fromType = "SYMBOL",     # ID | Input ID type: gene symbol
                toType = "ENTREZID",     # IDENTREZ ID | Output ID type: ENTREZ ID
                OrgDb = "org.Mm.eg.db")  #  | Mouse annotation database

Acquisition of ENTREZ ID for non model organisms

Model organisms, please skip this paragraph and proceed directly to Enrichment Analysis.

reference material:

-Guangchuang Yus official account:< https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/lHKZtzpN2k9uPN7e6HjH3w >

-AnnotationHub package documentation:< https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/AnnotationHub/inst/doc/AnnotationHub.html >

Preparation work:

Save the annotation file of the correspondence between gene names and ENTREZ IDs to a local file. In the future, when you want to obtain ENTREZ IDs for the same genome version, simply import this Zmays (species name) AH66225 (version). sqlite file is sufficient. Taking corn as an example:

Hub<- AnnotationHub() # It takes about 2 minutes, and if the internet speed is slow, it will take even longer

#Check which species are in AnnotationHub and remember AH in column idx***
#d <- display(hub) 

#Or simply search for 'zea' (a part of the Latin name for corn)
query(hub, "zea") 

maize_db_candidates <- query(hub, c("Zea mays", "OrgDb"))

#Download "AH61838" here
Maize.db<- hub [['AH117409 '] # It takes about 3 minutes, and if the internet speed is slow, it will take even longer

#View the number of genes included
length(keys(maize.db)) 
#Check how many IDs are included
columns(maize.db)
#What do the IDs of the first few genes look like
select(maize.db, keys(maize.db)[1:3], 
c("REFSEQ", "SYMBOL"), #The ID you want to obtain
"ENTREZID")

#Save to file
saveDb(maize.db, "Zmays.AH66225.sqlite")

#  | Read differentially expressed genes data
gsym.fc <- read.csv("easy_input_Zm.csv")
#  | View the first few rows of the data
head(gsym.fc)
#  | Check the dimensions of the data
dim(gsym.fc)

#  | Load the locally saved maize annotation database
maize.db <- loadDb("Zmays.AH66225.sqlite")

# ENTREZ ID | Convert gene symbols to ENTREZ IDs
gsym.id <- bitr(gsym.fc$SYMBOL,     #  | Column containing gene symbols
                "SYMBOL",           # ID | Input ID type: gene symbol
                "ENTREZID",         # IDENTREZ ID | Output ID type: ENTREZ ID
                maize.db)           #  | Maize annotation database
#  | View the first few rows of the conversion result
head(gsym.id)
#  | Check the dimensions of the conversion result
dim(gsym.id)

# ENTREZ ID | Merge gene symbols, ENTREZ IDs and fold change values
idvec <- gsym.id$ENTREZID           # ENTREZ ID | Create a vector of ENTREZ IDs
names(idvec) <- gsym.id$SYMBOL      #  | Set names of the vector to gene symbols
gsym.fc$ENTREZID <- idvec[gsym.fc$SYMBOL]  # ENTREZ ID | Map ENTREZ IDs to the original data
#  | View the first few rows of the merged data
head(gsym.fc)
#  | Check the dimensions of the merged data
dim(gsym.fc)

# CSV | Save the processed data to a CSV file
write.csv(gsym.fc[,c(3,2)], "very_easy_input_Zm.csv",  # 3(ENTREZID)2() | Select column 3 (ENTREZID) and column 2 (expression value)
          quote = F,          #  | Do not quote fields
          row.names = F)      #  | Do not save row names

Enrichment analysis

Reference materials:< http://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/clusterProfiler/inst/doc/clusterProfiler.html#supported -organisms>

If you have already completed the enrichment analysis and saved it in the format of enrichGO_output. csv, you can skip this part and directly enter Convert the enrichment analysis results output by clusterProfiler to the format required by GOplot

# ENTREZ IDlog2 | Read ENTREZ ID and log2 fold change data
# ENTREZ IDlog2foldchange | Assume ENTREZ ID is in the first column and log2foldchange in the second column
id.fc <- read.csv("very_easy_input_Mm.csv", as.is = T)
#  | View the first few rows of the data
head(id.fc)
##   ENTREZID    log2fc
## 1    11990 -0.308724
## 2    12290 -0.352114
## 3    12291 -0.300020
## 4    12334 -0.199424
## 5    12552 -0.206564
## 6    12561 -0.500161
#  | Check the dimensions of the data
dim(id.fc)
## [1] 201   2
# (GO) | Perform Gene Ontology (GO) enrichment analysis
ego <- enrichGO(gene = id.fc$ENTREZID,         # (ENTREZ ID) | Input gene list (ENTREZ IDs)
                #  -  | Select species annotation database - use this line for mouse
                OrgDb = org.Mm.eg.db,
                #  | Use this line for human
                #OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,
                #  | Use this line for non-model organisms like maize
                #OrgDb = maize.db,
                ont = "BP",                   # GO: BP()MF()CC() | Select GO ontology: BP (Biological Process), MF (Molecular Function), or CC (Cellular Component)
                pAdjustMethod = "BH",         # pBenjamini-Hochberg | P-value adjustment method: Benjamini-Hochberg
                #pvalueCutoff  = 0.001,      # p() | Raw p-value cutoff (commented out)
                qvalueCutoff  = 0.01)        # q | Adjusted q-value cutoff
#  | Check the dimensions of the enrichment results
dim(ego)
## [1] 334  12
# CSV | Save the enrichment analysis results to a CSV file
write.csv(ego, "enrichGO_output.csv", quote = F)  #  | Do not quote fields

enrichplot

https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/enrichplot/inst/doc/enrichplot.html

Draw using the built-in functions of enrichplot

Reference materials:< https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/enrichplot/inst/doc/enrichplot.html >

# ENTREZ ID | Convert ENTREZ IDs to gene symbols for better readability
egox <- setReadable(ego, 'org.Mm.eg.db', #  | Select species annotation database
                    'ENTREZID')           # IDENTREZ ID | Specify input ID type as ENTREZ ID

#  | Prepare gene expression data for visualization
geneList <- id.fc$log2fc                  # log2 | Extract log2 fold change values
names(geneList) <- id.fc$ENTREZID         # ENTREZ ID | Set names of the gene list to ENTREZ IDs

# - | Plot circular gene-function enrichment network
cnetplot(egox, 
         foldChange = geneList,           #  | Show gene expression fold change
         #foldChange = NULL,             # () | Do not show fold change (commented out)
         circular = TRUE,                 #  | Set circular layout
         #node_label = FALSE,            # () | Hide gene names if too many (commented out)
         showCategory = 4,                # term | Number of enriched terms to display
         colorEdge = TRUE)                #  | Color edges by relationship type
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `linewidth` instead.

# PDF | Save circular plot to PDF file
ggsave("clusterProfiler_circle.pdf", width = 8, height = 5)

# -() | Plot non-circular gene-function enrichment network
cnetplot(egox, 
         foldChange = geneList,           #  | Show gene expression fold change
         #foldChange = NULL,             # () | Do not show fold change (commented out)
         #circular = TRUE,               # () | Disable circular layout (commented out)
         #node_label = FALSE,            # () | Hide gene names (commented out)
         showCategory = 4,                # term | Number of enriched terms to display
         colorEdge = TRUE)                #  | Color edges by relationship type

# PDF | Save non-circular plot to PDF file
ggsave("clusterProfiler_not_circle.pdf", width = 8, height = 5)

# GO | Prepare data frame for GO enrichment results
go <- data.frame(Category = "BP",               # (Biological Process) | Set category to Biological Process
                 ID = ego$ID,                    # GOID | GO term ID
                 Term = ego$Description,         # GO | GO term description
                 Genes = gsub("/", ", ", ego$geneID), # ID | Replace gene ID separator from '/' to ', '
                 adj_pval = ego$p.adjust)        # p | Adjusted p-value

#  | Read gene expression fold change data
id.fc <- read.csv("very_easy_input_Mm.csv", as.is = T)

#  | Integrate enrichment results with expression data

        space = 0.02,           #  | Gap between gene blocks
        gene.order = 'logFC',   # log2 | Order genes by log2 fold change
        lfc.col = c('darkgoldenrod1', 'black', 'cyan1'),  #  | Custom color palette for fold change
        gene.space = 0.25,      #  | Distance between gene names and circle
        gene.size = 8,          #  | Font size for gene names

#  | Plot gene enrichment cluster diagram
GOCluster(circ.gsym, go$Term[1:n],              # nGO term | Use top n enriched GO terms
          clust.by = 'logFC',                   #  | Cluster genes by log2 fold change
          #clust.by = 'term',                   # term() | Cluster genes by enriched terms (commented out)
          lfc.col = c('darkgoldenrod1', 'black', 'cyan1'), #  | Custom color palette for fold change
          lfc.space = 0.05,                     #  | Space between fold change and tree
          lfc.width = 0.01,                     #  | Width of fold change circles
          term.col = mycol[1:n],                # term | Assign colors to terms
          term.space = 0.05,                    # term | Space between terms and fold change
          term.width = 0.15)                    # term | Width of term circles
